50|$|His 1954 novel Tomorrow! dealt {{graphically}} {{with the}} civilian impact of <b>thermonuclear</b> <b>war</b> {{to make a}} case for a strong Civil Defense network in the United States, as he told the story of two neighboring cities (one prepared, one unprepared) before and after an attack by missile-armed Soviet bombers. This was adapted in 1956 by ABC Radio, as a one-hour drama narrated by Orson Welles.|$|E
50|$|Herman Kahn in his tome On <b>Thermonuclear</b> <b>War,</b> has {{posited that}} a broken-backed war is implausible, simply because one side would likely absorb vastly more damage than its opposition. As {{he was writing}} in the late 1950s, when the nuclear arsenals of the Soviet Union and the United States {{numbered}} {{in the tens of}} thousands, the validity of this statement in the modern war can be called into question.|$|E
